Third-Person Plural:


[Dikduk/Hebrew/Binyanim/Pi’el]

* Pi’el: The “pi’el” (פִּעֵל) is one of the [[hebrew binyanim]]. <small>{{[[binyan|(?)]]}}</small>
- If you take a [[shoresh]] like כתב which means “writing” and put it in the _pi’el_ binyan, it produces a verb that is a more “intense” form of writing, i.e. “engraving.”
===
> [[learn more about the _pi’el_|More]]
===

Learn more about the _pi’el_:
Here is more information about the _pi’el_:
- Verbs in the _pi’el_ have the properties of being [[active]] and [[intensive]].
- The _pi’el_ [[Pi’el tenses|has various verb forms]].
- The _pi’el_ corresponds to the [[_pa’el_]] in Aramaic.
- The _pi’el_ [[is one of the “heavy” binyanim due to its doubled middle letter]].
- The _pi’el_ is one of the binyanim that can accept [[four-letter shorushim]]

Is one of the “heavy” binyanim due to its doubled middle letter: Verbs in the _pi’el_ are called “heavy.”
- This is because they are pronounced with a doubled middle letter.
- For example, the shoresh קדש when put in the _pi’el_ produces the verb מְקַדֵּשׁ (_meka*d’d*esh)_ “he is donating to the temple.”


[Dikduk/Hebrew/Binyanim/Pi’el/Tenses]

* Pi’el Tenses:
Verbs in the [[_pi’el_]] have conjugations in various “tenses”:
| [[_Pi’el_ Past Tense|Past Tense <br> (of the _pi’el_)]] | [[_Pi’el_ Future Tense|Future Tense <br> (of the _pi’el_)]] | [[_Pi’el_ Active Participle|Active Participle <br> (of the _pi’el_)]] |
| [[_Pi’el_ Imperative|Imperative <br> (of the _pi’el_)]] | [[_Pi’el_ Infinitive|Infinitive <br> (of the _pi’el_)]] | \^ |


[Dikduk/Hebrew/Binyanim/Pi’el/Tenses/Active Participle]

* _Pi’el_ Active Participle: 
The [[{{_pi’el_}} binyan]] <small>{{[[binyan|(?)]]}}</small> has an [[{{active participle}} form]].
The _pi’el_ active participle form has the following conjugation pattern for [[regular shorushim]] like זמן:
|    \x      | *Masculine* | *Feminine* |
| *Singular* | [#[Masculine Singular|מְזַמֵּן <br><br> _m’zamein_ <br><br><br> [he is] inviting]] | [#[Feminine Singular|מְזַמֶּנֶת <br><br> _m’zamenes_ <br><br><br> [she is] inviting]] |
| *Plural*   | [#[Masculine Plural|מְזַמְּנִים <br><br> _m’zamnim_ <br><br><br> [those men are] inviting]] | [#[Feminine Plural|מְזַמְּנוֹת <br><br> _m’zamnos_ <br><br><br> [those women are] inviting]] |
===
> [[More]]
===

More:
- The _pi’el_ active participle corresponds to the [[_pa’el_ active participle]] of Aramaic.
- The _pi’el_ active participle features a מ prefix in all of its forms, making it easy to mistake for several other forms. <small>{{[[similar forms|→]]}}</small>
- Participles can either be verbs, or they can be used as nouns, referring to someone or something that does the given action.

Similar forms:
The _pi’el_ active participle e.g. מְקַדֵּשׁ which beings with a מ prefix looks similar to:
- The passive intensive _pu’al_ active participle e.g מְקוּדָּשׁ <small>{{[[pual active participle|→]]}}</small>
  - (The lack of a ו or ֻ  after the first letter differentiates it from the _pi’el_ active participle from its passive the _pu’al_.)
- The active causative _hif’il_ active participle e.g. מַקְדִּישׁ <small>{{[[hifil active participle|→]]}}</small>
  - (The lack of a י between the second and third root letters differentiates the pi’el active participle from a hif’il)
- The passive causative _huf’al_ active participle e.g. מוּקְדָּשׁ <small>{{[[hufal active participle|→]]}}</small>
  - (The lack of a ו or ֻ  after the first letter differentiates the _pi’el_ active participle from the _huf’al_.)


[Dikduk/Hebrew/Binyanim/Pi’el/Tenses/Future]

* _Pi’el_ Future Tense: The [[_pi’el_]] binyan has a [[future tense]], which is one of the [[Pi’el tenses|“tenses” of the _pi’el_ binyan]].
The _pi’el_ future tense follows these conjugations for [[regular shorushim]] like זמן:
|    \x    | *Singular* |\<| *Plural* |\< |
| *First-Person* | [[First-Person Singular|אֲזַמֵּן <br><br> _azamein_ <br><br><br> I will invite]] | \< | [[First-Person Plural|נְזַמֵּן <br><br> _nezamein_ <br><br><br> We will invite]] | \< |
| *Second-Person* | [[Second-Person Masculine Singular|תְּזַמֵּן <br><br> _tezamein_ <br><br><br> You [male] will invite]] | [[Second-Person Feminine Singular|תְּזַמְּנִי <br><br> _tezamni_ <br><br><br> You [female] will invite]]  | [[Second-Person Masculine Plural|תְּזַמְּנוּ <br><br> _tezamnu_ <br><br><br> You [males] will invite]] | [[Second-Person Feminine Plural|תְּזַמֵּנָּה <br><br> _tezameinnau_ <br><br><br> You [females] will invite]] |
| *Third-Person* | [[Third-Person Masculine Singular|יְזַמֵּן <br><br> _yezamein_ <br><br><br> He will invite]] | [[Third-Person Feminine Singular|תְּזַמֵּן <br><br> _tezamein_ <br><br><br> She will invite]]  | [[Third-Person Masculine Plural|יְזַמְּנוּ <br><br> _yezamnu_ <br><br><br> [Those males] will invite]]  | [[Third-Person Feminine Plural|תְּזַמֵּנָּה <br><br> _tezameinnau_ <br><br><br> [Those females] will invite]] |
- The _pi’el_ future tense corresponds to the [[_pa’el_ future tense]] of Aramaic.

