* בקידושיה:


* בשלוחה: The letters בשלוחה, _u’b’shluchah_, are probably:
- The [[prefix ו]], meaning and/or, pronounced “oo” when before a ב.
- The [[prefix ב]] which has various [[Prefix ב#Meanings|meanings]] including “in,” “with,” and “on,” (pronounced “b” when starting a syllable, as opposed to “v.”)
- The Hebrew word [[שָׁלוּחַ]], which can mean “[something] is sent” or “a person/thing that is sent.” Here, because the word is followed by “his,” we see that it must mean “a person/thing that is sent.”
- The [[Hebrew Possessive Suffixes#Third-person masculine singular for masculine singular noun|“possessive” suffix ו]], meaning “his” or “its.”
- Putting that all together, it means “and/or, in/with/on/etc, his/its, sent person/thing.”


* בשלוחו: The letters בשלוחו _u’b’shlucho_ probably:
- The [[prefix ו]], meaning and/or, pronounced “oo” when before a ב.
- The [[prefix ב]] which has various [[Prefix ב#Meanings|meanings]] including “in,” “with,” and “on,” (pronounced “b” when starting a syllable, as opposed to “v.”)
- The Hebrew word [[שָׁלוּחַ]], which can mean “is sent” or “a person/thing that is sent.” Here, because the word is followed by “his,” we see that it must mean “a person/thing that is sent.”
- The [[Hebrew Possessive Suffixes#Third-person masculine singular for masculine singular noun|“possessive” suffix ו]], meaning “his” or “its.”
- Putting that all together, it means “and/or, in/with/on/etc, his/its, sent person/thing.”


* בשתי:


* בתו: The letters בתו are probably:
- The Hebrew word [[בַּת]], meaning daughter.
- The Hebrew suffix ו meaning “his.” (<small>{{[[Hebrew Possessive Suffixes#Third-person masculine singular for masculine singular noun|more]]}}</small>)
- The combination is pronounced בִּתּוֹ, _bito_.


* גֶּבֶר: The Hebrew word גֶּבֶר is a wor for “man.” 
The word גֶּבֶר can denote a than the alternative Hebrew word for “man,” [[אִישׁ]].


* גבי:


* גברא: גברא is an Aramaic word for “man,” possibly with a connotation of a less important or praise-worthy man, as in the phrase “ההוא גברא,” i.e. “that man [did such and such],” which the Gemara sometimes uses to introduce a story about a person doing something inadvisable.


* גדולה:


* גוף:


* גופו:


* גופים:


* גמרא:


* גמ’: The letters גמ’‏ are an abbreviation for גמרא, _gemara_. When this abbreviation appears in the Gemara, it is the publisher indicating that a quotation from the Mishnah has ended, and what follows is the Gemara’s commentary on that Mishnah.


* דִּילְמָא: The Aramaic word דִּילְמָא _dilma_ means “maybe.”
- It is similar to the Hebrew word שֶׁמָּא _shema_. <small>{{[[שֶׁמָּא|→]]}}</small>


* דֶּרֶךְ אֶרֶץ: The Hebrew phrase דֶּרֶךְ אֶרֶץ _derech eretz_ “way of the land” has several connotations:
- It can mean that something is appropriate or polite
- It can also refer to working to support oneself financially
- It is used in the name of a minor tractate of Talmud Bavli called דרך ארץ רבה, _derech eretz rabah_ which discusses proper behavior.


* דּוּ: The word דּוּ has various meanings, such as “who,” “which is,” “since he,” etc.
It can also be part of the phrase טַן דּוּ sometimes spelled טַנְדּוּ, meaning “with grief/trouble.” <small>{{[[טַנְדּוּ|→]]}}</small>
Jastrow:
> דּוּ I  (= רְּהוּ, cmp. דִּי) who, which is, since he, it, &c. Y. Sabb. XIX, beg. 16ᵈ דו אמר … הוא דאמר the same that says …, says also &c. Y. Peah I, 15ᶜ top בגין דו בעי וכ׳ because he wants to teach &c. Y. Maasr. I, 49ᵃ bot. מן דו from the time that. Y. Gitt. IX, 50ᶜ top nobody says ‘even’ אלא דו מודה וכ׳ except he admits the preceding; a. fr. 
> דּוּ II  c. (= דֵּן) this, that. Y. Naz. IV, end, 53ᶜ. Y. Erub. V, 22ᶜ top דו ואַלְפַּיִם itself (the whole area of the town) and two thousand cubits beside. 
> דּוּ III  (δύο, only in certain compounds) two, double. Lev. R. s. 14, beg. דו פרצופין נברא Adam was created with two faces (male and female persons combined); Gen. R. s. 8, beg. דיו; Ber. 68ᵃ; a. e.—Ex. R. s. 5 דו פרצ׳ היה יוצא the word of the Lord went forth in two characters (killing and reviving). V. דְּיוֹ II.


