* קבל: The letters קבל could be the Hebrew word [[קִבֵּל]].


* קדושיה:


* קטנה: The letters קטנה are probably the Hebrew word [[קְטַנָּה]].


* קטנות:


* קידושין: The letters קידושין are probably the Aramaic word [[קִידּוּשִׁין]] _kiddushin_ meaning marriage or specifically the halachic pre-marital engagement status.


* קפדא:

== ritvah?


* קשיא:


* קתני:


* רַב: The Aramaic and Hebrew word רַב has several usages:
- It can can mean “big”
- It can be a title for a Rabbi
- It can be the name of Rav i.e. אַבָּא אָרִיכָא _Aba Aricha_, a famous Rabbi of the Talmud who lived in Babylonia.


* רָבָא: The name רָבָא _Rava_ refers to a Talmudic Rabbi who lived in Babylonia.


* ראתהו:


* רב: The letters רב are probably the Hebrew and Aramaic word רַב _rav_ meaning “large” or “Rabbi.” <small>{{[[רַב|→]]}}</small>


* רבא: The letters רבא could be the name רָבָא _Rava_, a Talmudic Rabbi who lived in Babylonia.


* רבי:


* רוצה:


* ריש:


* רישא: The letters רישא are probably the Aramaic word רֵישָׁא _reisha_ meaning “head” or “top.”


* רל:


* ר״ל: The letters ר״ל could be:
- An abbreviation for the Talmudic Rabbi רֵישׁ לָקִישׁ _Reish Lakesh_
- An abbreviation for the phrase רָצוֹן לוֹמַר, meaning “he intends to say”


* שֶׁמָּא: The Hebrew word שֶׁמָּא can mean “maybe,” or “perhaps.”
- It is often used in expressing the reason for a Rabbinic decree, as in “the Rabbis forbade such and such because _shema_ someone might come to do a Torah prohibition”
- It corresponds to the Aramaic word [[דִּילְמָא]].


* שָׁלוּחַ: The Hebrew word שָׁלוּחַ (_shaluach_) has various meanings:
- It can mean “is sent” as in המכתב שלוח, (_hamichtav shaluach_, “the letter is sent.”)
- It can mean “something or someone who is sent” such as a messenger, (הַשָּׁלוּחַ, _hashaluach_, “the one who is sent.”)
===
> [[More]]
===

More:
The Hebrew word שָׁלוּחַ can be identified as follows <small>{{[[Identifying verbs|(?)]]}}</small>:
- The word שלוח comes from the [[shoresh שלח]]
- Grammatically, it is a [[passive participle]]
- It comes from the Hebrew binyan [[Binyanim/pa’al]].
- See [[{|regular conjugations for }pa’al passive participle{|s}]].


* שאנו:


* שבכל:


* שבת:


* שהוא:


* שהיא:


* שהנשים:


* שחייב:


* שיבוטא: The letters שיבוטא are probably the Aramaic word שִׁבּוּטָא, which seems to have been a kind of large fish, although from that Rashi defines it in several places perhaps we see that it wasn’t a common word that every reader would know.


* שייך:


* שיכול:


* שיקדש: The letters שיקדש are probably:
- The Hebrew prefix ש meaning “that”
- One of several Hebrew verbs spelled יקדש, which can have various meanings. <small>{{[[More|→]]}}</small>

More:
We see from the י prefix that the letters יקדש are a third-person mascuine [[future tense]] verb from the [[shoresh קדש]].
- It could be the Hebrew _pa’al_ if there were such a form <small>{{[[Paal Past Tense#Third-Person Masculine Singular|→]]}}</small>
- It could be the Hebrew _pi’el_ יְקַדֵּשׁ _yekadesh_ <small>{{[[Piel Past Tense#Third-Person Masculine Singular|→]]}}</small>


* שיראנה: The letters שיראנה are probably:
- The Hebrew prefix ש meaning “that”
- The word יִרְאֶנָּה meaning “he will see”


